text: Well after a long long wait we finally get a glimpse of how Michael Bay is going to do the Turtle. I want to say it looks promising. As many people mentioned before I prefured the goofyness of the 90's turtles. Michael Bay want's to be more serious with the turtles. I don't like that very much. I love a good action movie as the next person but The Turtles was a mixture of humor and action for me, and it always blended very well in the older movies (Even the 3rd one. Yes I said it) Nostalgia Critic said it best though " The older movies aren't going anywhere, you can still enjoy them. It's just people are always going to try for newwer itterations." He said that after the Avatar movie bombed, and I would also like to add Its up to you the people if these versions of what is now or what once was to be popular. I like Michael Bay as a director, but he really is all Action and advanced CGI. I would have taken the old puppet controlled 90's masks over this cgi stuff. Having said that this might be a good movie provided they make SENSE of the turtles mutation other then they NEEDED hero's (like the ooze accidently falling in the sewers and turtles HAPPENED to find them). Becuase frankly I would be very very pissed if they where all like " We need hero's to protect our city. We need a symbol. Something that's never been done before. Turtle's yes. Lets make super turtle heros" If Michael Bay goes that route I will have lost all hope for humanity lol. They better freaken have Splinter in this. I will be upset if he is not apart of this. so here's to him being there and (despite some of the plot changes) here's too hoping this will actually be a good movie. Oh and on a final note, I don't know if I like the voice for Michaelangelo. Just hire back the voice actor from before. They better give him some good comedic lines and keep the rest of the characters personallities intact.

text: I hope this turns out as dark as I remember the graphic novels were back in High School. Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles redefined the way comics were trending at the time. It was combination of a complex NYC gang story fused with supernatural characters and Alien Brains trying to take over the world. The story kept evolving like the mutants themselves. Plus awesome support and main character balances that really brought the story to life.  It was over the top science fiction meets action and had a good balance to it that kept you wanting more. This year is summing up to be pretty good on comic book movies and tv shows. Wish I kept up on my pursuits in this genre of work cause its rewarding seeing people appreciate the creative complexity of comics potential.  Give this a Q('-'Q) meow POW POW!!! rating- cabbit

text: I feel like movie goers are all too critical these days.  If you go to IMDB, everybody apparently values their opinion as official fact.  As if they're all certified gods of movie making because they watched SO many movies.  It really is sad.  It's the same thing as constantly pleasuring yourself multiple times a day and then calling yourself a porn star. (Sorry to be graphic, but it's true.)  We're lucky to have the freedoms of entertainment that we do.  We're lucky to be able to progress something we valued as children into future generations.  This TMNT reboot is a perfect 'when I was your age' opportunity for our own children.  All this nit-picky nonsense irritates me.  Typical American spirit of entitlement.  Just enjoy the film.  Good grief.

text: What people who are killing everyone on here for bashing the film are forgetting ... we all want the same thing.  A good film that  keeps the TMNT fans ( old and new ) happy. I was born in the 1980's ... the beginning of the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles popularity when the comics began, the original cartoon began ( and blew up ) and the first 1990 film continued to make the franchise huge. The thing about their look is this, if you can't satisfy the old fans as well as the new, keep them at least similar to what most of us grew up loving and make the movie as well as the original ( so a new generation of kids can love the Turtles like i did as a kid ) then WHY MAKE THE MOVIE? They CLEARLY casted Megan Fox based on name alone, because it'd draw in fans ... but heres the problem... does she fit the character ? probally not. What the director of this film should of learned is that they didn't need a star actress to play April, because using the then unknown Judith Hoag was a great choice because she was April O' Neil. Then you got their look..... the Turtles are twice the size of any human, but in each one of the series ( cartoon, comic book and movies ) the turtles were only a couple of inches taller than them. They were human like turtles ... which is why the mutation made them smarter, stronger ex... than their enemies ( the foot clan ). So why are they seven feet tall ? And why is there complaints about them having noses... noses are what humans have ... and in EVERY one of the turtles cartoons, movies and even in the comic books they never looked that way. If they cant follow simple things like making them look right, why not give them five fingers and toes. Hell why not just give them beards and make them wear t-shirts and pants like humans do. Come on ppl..... if the directors can't even follow simple rules to keeping their origin story, look, ex... right... how do you expect them to make a great movie.  Thats why Spiderman 3 flopped ...they couldn't even get Venom's origin story correct and made the Spiderman character a dancing goof !!! Why do you think the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles 3 movie was so bad? they couldn't even create a great plot for the movie, the costumes looked horrible, and they dumbed down the whole movie.  For the guy who directed this... LEARN FROM PAST HISTORY... dont ruin this franchise again !

text: *deep breath*  Okay.  First off, I completely understand that Michael Bay is producing a darker, edgier TMNT. Check. Second off, I understand that he does action scenes, so naturally a movie produced by him will have his signature set of explosions and that it will probably be 60% CG. I understand that it is directed by Jonathan Liebesman, not Michael Bay. I understand that I have no right to call Megan Fox a bad actress. And I understand that Peter Laird wouldn't let anyone truly screw up the TMNT. I also understand that perhaps the backstory of the accident in the sewers still qualifies here.  Here's what I do not understand.  (NOTE: I will not go into details on the large issues with this movie. I feel like the major issues with TMNT fans have been thoroughly in the scathing pool of comments that lurks just beneath mine.)  First off, what's with the lens flares? It's like Star Trek: Into Darkness. At least in Star Trek, where literally everything has to have a blinking light on it, it makes sense. (Don't get me wrong, I love Star Trek.)  Second off, though I know Meagan Fox is a professional actress, I don't think she makes a good April O'Neil. (Then again, I'm not the casting director.) In fact, as I watch her in this trailer, she looks like she doesn't even want to be there, which makes me wonder, "Then why is she?"  A note to the costume director; at least, for the love of all canon, for the sake of consistency, make her have red hair. That is a must. An absolute must. If April O' Neil is a brunette, you may very well be guaranteed that you'll never hear the end of it.  Thirdly, if Nickelodeon is a patron of this movie, I would hope that it will not be solidly action and petty humor. I like Nickelodeon. What I do not like is an action movie that consists of solid plot exposition for an hour, then suddenly explosions, and then roll credits. Oh, and throw in some bodily humor and screaming Megan Fox. Please do not give me that. You can bet your femur that I will not pay money to sit through two hours of it, that's for sure, and neither will America's parents.  I love TMNT, and I'm trying really, really hard to like this movie. Honestly, I am. But I feel like I'm just getting force-fed Transformers 4: Extraterresturtle Explosions feat. Meagan Fox (Again). But then, who am I to judge? This is my opinion, and I'd be very glad to receive any feedback that would lessen my negative opinions.

text: 1. CG is fine (and the most appropriate option), but designs should have been inspired by a "Bruce Lee-type" physique, not roided-out gorillas. Turtles were always about not underestimating the power hidden in unlikely places. 2. Plot emphasis should have been on forging an emotional connection to ancient martial arts, honor through traditional discipline, and loyalty. 3. Casting needs to be more racially diverse and inspired: April was half black in the original comic. Maybe she should have been asian. Honestly, whoever is best in the role. It shouldn't matter anymore. 4. Burry Michael Bay in the dessert, never speak of him again. Call Guillermo del Toro from now on. 5. Give the film a unique camera style or color palette, ANYTHING for god's sake. This could be Transformers or Spiderman or any generic summer film. Where is the personality?

text: Everyone's gonna gripe about something, I grew up watching tmnt and loved the crap out of it. Even watched the original movies loved them too.  Time has changed I think it looks pretty cool, what little is shown. It doesn't have to follow the original series or be like the classic movies, since they didn't follow the original comic series(which was a little more darker than the laugh out loud version).  So why does this have to be the exact same? It doesn't.  Don't hate things before you even see it based on previous versions.  I remember people freaked out about the newer batman, saying it wont compare to the original 2.  However, it was proven to be an awesome trilogy.  You think by now folks you'd realize things don't always follow the original.  I mean just about all the super hero movies are like that.  This might be an awesome spin on tmnt bringing in some of the original comic style dark with hopefully a little comedic relief as well.  So I'm not going to say I hate or love it till I see it.  So stop your complaining about all the little details, and by the way the yellow jumpsuit would look retarded now, just saying.

text: I like what I see so far.  As a huge TMNT fan as I am, I'm glad to see another "realistic" kind of TMNT movie.  Hopefully it ends up being a good movie, but if not I won't complain like some of the people on here are already doing.  I mean in all honesty even if it ends up being a bad movie, I don't see how it will "hurt" or "ruin" anything. It may show that the makers of this film are not good at making TMNT movies, but to say it will "ruin" the TMNT series is just idiotic.  The series will forever live on and be just fine.  Quite frankly I don't see the big fuss about Bay being involved.  Sure he he might have bad movies to some but he has good movies as well.  I'm just glad we finally get a chance to see another TMNT movie.  Too many people are just too picky.

text: Two words: Turtle lips.       They just look really ugly, but that's not the worst part.  The fact that they have a human skull with reptilian features - the nose and the skin, in particular - with two very human eyes peeking out behind all of that turtle meat that makes up their meaty faces... and the lips, the human lips means that for the whole film, you have to watch those lips move as they speak in human fashion, in a mockery of a real person. It's a nosedive into the uncanny valley.       The puppet Turtles from the 80's live action films seem to represent the Ninja Turtles better because they have beaks and large Muppet eyes, and they look endearing, but this just reminds me of something that is human, and at the same time shouldn't be human.  Very strange, I think.

It was supposed to be cartoony, wacky and fun, not some ''The world's balance is hanging on us, we need to save the world''. Baxter's gadgets broke often and were kinda secondhand quality level (or more like *thirdhand*), Bebop and Rocksteady were always messing up and failing to beat the Turtles, and even the Turtles themselves were eating pizza and chilling out, when Shredder was planning on his next move.

text: Here is a breakdown of the plot. The Shredder wants the city to give him money to continue his experiments whilst looking like a respectable Business man. The foot are Terrorizing the city. The Shredder says he has a solution and he creates the Turtles to stop the foot. We then find out the Shredder is behind the foot he wants a lot more money of the city. He uses the Turtles in his plans and they find out the truth, that the Shredder is behind the foot at the same time April O'neill finds out the truth. The Turtles escape with help from another one of Shredders experiments a rat called Splinter. They find out that April is on Shredders case, so they decide to contact her and see if she wants to team up, which she agrees to. The Shredder sends his men after  the Turtles and they eventually find out the Turtles are staying in the sewers so they search the sewers and eventually find them and attack the Turtles layer. But whilst they are searching for th turtles they are still terrorizing the city with the turtles trying to stop them every chance they get. The Turtles escape but splinter stays to help them get away. Splinter is taken to Shredder where he keeps him captive. The turtles find out and decide to rescue him. They go to Shredders layer and fight the Foot eventually defeating them in the final battle, The Shredder puts on a suit of armor to fight the turtles with. In the final battle the turtles and Splinter manage to defeat the Shredder, but they don't kill him.  A couple of extras: 1. their will be a time difference of at least 3-6 Months between the turtles Escaping and the final battle. 2. The Shredder lives Because William Fitchner who plays the Shredder revealed he has a 3 film contract. Sorry if I didn't spell his name right. 3. The Ooze which Shredder uses to create the turtles is alien in origin.

text: I'm surprised that Mikey's face is what most fans are complaining about. I mean, it does look a bit weird when you're used to seeing the turtles with the very stylized proportions of a cartoon, but personally, I'm ok with their new appearance, considering how hard it must have been to keep them recognizeable while making them look realistic. Anyway, I never imagined that real-life mutant turtles would be a particularly enchanting sight...  One thing that does bother me though is how the plot is presented so far. From what I understand from this trailer, the "narrator", who appears to be an American Shredder (?), is telling April that he and her father worked together (!) and created the turtles (!!) specifically with the intention to make them heroes (!!!) who would somehow help lower the criminality rate in New York... I, just- what ?! Since when has the Shredder cared about the population, where's the Foot Clan ? If he intentionally created the turtles, what reason would he have to be against them, since they're fighting crime just as he apparently wanted (unless he only said that to hide his real motives) ? And what about Splinter's origin story ? Was he also meant to be some kind of mutated superhero, or could it be that he's actually April's father who was victim of yet another lab accident ?!  I'm not sure what to think so far. I wouldn't mind a few changes to the original story, but this new movie looks like a complete reimagining of the entire context, about which I'm a bit skeptical so far. I'm still willing to give it a chance because I think it looks pretty cool anyway, but my appreciation of the movie will mostly depend on the directing, the way the story unfolds and to what extent I can still recognize the characters I love.

text: As a die hard TMNT fan, I was really hoping that this movie would bring a look into the darker aspects of this series. I understand the appeal for a redesign, everyone's doing it, Superman, Batman, The Avengers however, with the Turtles who are not just iconic in costume but also their biological form, this will, for most fans, be hard to bare. Yet, this could have been adaptable as long as the movie's other facets held their own. Then you had to shove Megan Fox, an actress who should never haven risen further then the set of a cheesy horror film, into the movie as none other then April O'Neil .... I idolized April as a young girl. She was confident, intelligent and tough, all the while having compassion and understanding. She was a woman worthy of the leading female role next to four, pizzaholic, mutant turtles. I understand reinventing April for the 21st century but throwing in a trashy looking, loud mouthed, wannabe actress with no potential to ever play a woman with anything considered a personality was an obvious down grade. Why not throw us an interesting curve ball? Julianne Hough? Gemma Arterton? Rooney Mara? Someone who, when you think about them, you'd be nodding in a curious satisfaction and be pleasantly surprised when you realized the actress might actually succeed and grow within the amazing role of April.... Instead of filling Megan Fox's pockets with rocks and hoping to hell she'll at least drown while destroying the franchise.

text: 1. April was always a cute, spunky, skinny white ginger. The bodytype, the nationality, and the haircolor don't match the character. The only reason, seemingly, Foxx would be in this movie is the connections to Bay, or because big boobies. Not cool.  2. The theme of the Ninja Turtles franchise has always been a dirty and slightly grimy, purple paletted smoky and fun crime world New York straight out of a late 80's ninja/action flick. Lens flair, sharp colors and clean streets don't fit the general theme that has been established in the past years.  3. The turtles look like donkey shit smeared in bile and putrefying piss. I don't think it needs to be said that they are too ugly and behemoth shaped to remain relatable. Their comedy will fall flat because of this. But knowing Micheal Bay that won't be a problem, as most of the jokes will be brown anyways.  This is perpetuation of the cancer that is CGI children movies. Smurfs didn't work, Transformers didn't work, Yogi Bear didn't work. LET THESE MASTERPIECES STAY DEAD!

text: meh, Megan Fox is April O'Neil... Change her hair color to red and it wont change the fact that its still Megan fox but it will make it more accurate. Kinda like Lois lane in superman movie the new one she lacked a certain gravitas and she didn't really have familiar features you look for when your a comic nerd (i'm not) to look at a trailer and say "that's Lois lane" besides the fact shes holding a camera. I could bring up the new spider man movie  but besides the fact that im over the high school super hero thing and it put me to sleep the first time I watched it, I have no gripes.  Also what rogue scientist sits in his lab and says "I have so and so amount of this mutagen and I have turtles... Eureka!"  Turtles were a accident in most of the incarnations of this story which doesn't make it more believable but makes it less like a lapse of judgment on the scientist part. it all holds up for nostalgia addicts but if your just trying to make a new movie  to draw in new fans then I have to say B.S.  I'm not going to see this movie only because I don't think I have the attention span for it (need more substance) but as long as it entertains the masses then it should be OK. Use to have the original VHS of the ninja turtles but their probably degraded beyond repair now and who has a VHS deck anymore or beta.    Probably just repeated some stuff some people said down the line but it never hurts to say it again.

text: This looks silly like Transformers.  Basically Michael Bay turned the turtles into CGi Transformer vehicles and they're fake.  The first TMNT movie in 1990 had real actors in real turtle costumes do real martial arts which was better than this CGi nonsense I think. Michael Bay admitted himself that he makes movies for teenage boys.  In order to make movies for the teenage age group it has to go through the MPAA to get a PG-13 rating which means a lot of the more realistic violence, language and adult themes have to be filtered out and dumbed down to appeal to young people.  The reason why Hollywood continues to make these silly unintellectual movies is because there's a big enough audience for it.  Just like how the music industry makes money off Justin Beiber because there's enough people willing to buy Beiber albums.  Just because Hollywood studios and music record companies make money off CGi movies and Beiber albums doesn't mean the taste of the audience is good.

text: I just had to comment again. You know, it's one thing to change a few things here and there to update the story, but when the story is what made the turtles so dear to everyone's heart and has been what has continued its success for so many years, the last thing you want to do is to try and change it to where it becomes almost unrecognizable. I mean, seriously, how hard is it tell the familiar story but with better special effects and stuff? Why is this person claiming to be Shredder when he's not Japanese, but Amurican? Why can't they make April look like she looked in the comics and the cartoon? Why do the foot carry guns when they are supposed to be ninjas? Why do the turtles look like the Hulk with armor? Why is Michael Bay still allowed to go near a film studio? Just...why? This movie is filled with "why's?" In fact, forget any kind of tagline they put on the movie posters. The movie poster should just read, "Michael Bay's Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles" with the tagline, "Why?" and it should end with  "Coming Soon to a dumpster near you 2014."

text: The turtles look like gigantic black women on steroids who had too much plastic surgery and were then painted green. Who thought it was a good idea to give them those fish lips and Shrek noses? They have never even *had* noses. And real turtles have just two slits for air, like most reptiles, so if you're going to go for realism do that. From a technical (computer graphics) perspective they are essentially the Hulk's kids and he has really, really ugly kids. This is a disaster in the making, it's already ruined. Shame about the great cast (Will Arnett, William Fichtner, Tony Shalhoub and Alan Ritchson) being wasted on what is clearly a half-baked creative vision.

Loser 90's babies/Y-gen hipster dumbasses  who think the turtles should look like the child-safe cartoon version or 90's film versions which were only mildly successful. This camp, which is all the people bitching and whining here, don't know shit about the original Eastmen and Laird vision nor have they read the early comics. These are all the people crying about their childhood being ruined. Umm your childhood was a basterdized version of the original vision, marketed to your parents as a safer, child-friendly, rendition. If you're crying because it doesn't look like what you know, then good. I'm so glad it doesn't look like the shit you grew up on and is finally starting to take a swift turn back to the original concept.

text: Why are you people getting so offensive over the new TMNT? It's ridiculous. The goals in this world are to try new things, develop new things, experiment new things. I'd also like to point out, Jonathan Liebesman is the director, NOT Michael Bay, he one of the producers. Yeah, I enjoyed the 80s franchise just as much as any other TMNT addict. But, it'd get boring if we kept the same thing going for another decade, for example, COD, all they did with they're games was change the weapons and landscape... Sorta, the lazy way. That game got boring realllll quick, just like this movie franchise would. I'd rather not be stuck in the stone age, I enjoy change, and eventually these guys would learn from they're mistakes if it doesn't turn out good just like Godzilla. Godzilla had a tremendous change in 1998, it sucked, they learned from it, now it's 2014 and it looks like an original mixed in with new, more sophisticated awesome tech. My point is, stop being so close minded, it's utter ignorance, you haven't even seen the movie, be open minded and don't judge until you've seen it, even when you do see it, be open to new change.

text: I will probably comment on all the trailers... This is a joke right? TMNT... more like transformers From the heavy cgi, music, stuff being blown up, weird designs for the turtles and not friendly voices and should i even mention... meagan fox as April!! What is this?!  Although it looks like a terrible rendition with cgi that just isn't appealing, I will give some good points for customizing the characters abilities and weapons. That was pretty neat to see, a modern take on what tools they can use, however the things i mentioned above will most likely make this movie another "summer" type movie that won't ever be a classic like the first live action films.  I would like to note that I am disappointed in the heavy use of cgi. Before cgi, they used make-up artists and other people in the field to create characters (although looking back many do look a bit silly), but with todays advancements in details and tools they could go without the cgi for a more personal feel rather than everything being 3d models (apart from people).

text: I think there are reboots and there are reboots-for-the-sake-of-reboots. Take for example another reboot: Batman Begins. It really did justice to a reboot because it kept the series fresh with new ideas.  But the reason I stress that it did justice was because the fresh ideas were believable. Everything made sense in BB - the way Wayne got access to his gadgets, the reason why the Bat costume had ears, the reason why his suit had Kevlar, the way Batman has a cowl in the neck of his costume, but does away with it in the sequel, etc.  Over here, this just seems like the blueprint of the Transformers movie had sex with the blueprint of TMNT, and out came a pile of jumbled up trash. This seems like it is trying very hard to be a credible attempt at a reboot.  A real reboot, like Batman Begins, seems effortless.  This seems like they had the mandate to make a reboot first, and then brainstormed how they should reboot it, rather than a TMNT fan having a genuine epiphany of creative genius, and deciding that a reboot was in order.

text: Okay, you know what I don't understand about all this? Fans of the original cartoons: "OMG they look hideous! I HATE this new design." "This is NOTHING like the old design! How creepy!" "They EXPECT us to pay to see THIS? Who would see those ugly monsters?" Hideous. Creepy. Ugly. Monsters.  ARE YOU EVEN LISTENING TO YOURSELVES? Since the very beginning, the turtles have established that they are indeed hideous creations to the human race, no matter how cartoony and cute they may have looked in the 80s, 90s, 2003 and 2012 series. To the other cartoon civilians, they were disturbing monsters, and had to hide using their ninja stealth and trenchcoats. Also, wasn't one of their BIGGEST LESSONS that they supposedly taught us as kids was that LOOKS. DO. NOT. MATTER???  I admit that I am fairly new to the franchise, and being a teenage girl I was much more drawn to their cuteness in the 2012 series. But after doing lengthy research on the franchise over the past 3 decades, from the comics up till now, I realized I didn't fall in love with their looks... but as an aspiring animator with a childlike heart, I fell in love with their unique story AND equally unique personalities. Also, they have to make difficult choices and learn lessons  through their adventures that help them grow as characters. I was mixed about it at first, but I might actually have to see this movie, even though I'm very aware it's nothing like the 2012 cartoon I currently adore. It looks much darker and more adult, but you know what? I am an adult and not a pink-and-doll-loving little girl anymore. Therefore, I think I can appreciate a good dark, adult action-comedy, if that what this turns out to be. And from the newer trailers I've seen, the turtles' personalities are VERY lively and true to the consistency of the franchise. True, they're not attractive, but this is 2014 PEOPLE. They can't look like the cuter 80s, 90s, or even 2012 cartoons if they want to get their emotions shown through facial expressions across in a live-action flick. They're not going to use cartoony puppets like the first one, because it's not DIFFERENT. Fresh and new is ESSENTIAL to any good film. The turtles have changed through SO many different interpretations over the years, and that should already be a lesson you've learned if you're over 13. Change happens. Life Happens. SERIOUSLY. I'm not even 20 yet, and I was able to figure that out. So please, people, enough with the butthurt'in and get over it. Nostalgia is a powerful emotion, I know that better than anyone. But it's just that, nostalgia. Time goes on. New memories are created. And with an open mind, you might find that the nostalgia can be found even in something like this.
author: Alexandra Reinert

text: I am a massive TMNT fan having loved the cartoons, live movies, video games, etc and I'm giving this movie a chance. Here's why. Yes the Turtles are quite a bit larger than other depictions but how can we honestly say how big or small a mutated turtle should or should not be? Even if you could pinpoint it, the need for accuracy goes out the window when you're talking about mutant turtles, a slow creature, being ninjas which is a very fast fighting style. They even use their bulk to their advantage (scene where Raph smokes a vehicle). Characteristics are intact. Leo is serious, Raph aggressive, Donny shy (at least off the hop with April) and Mikey is goofy. Also the fact they were originally going to be aliens in this film but the makers scrapped that idea due to fan rage. And I believe they are hinting at Shredder playing a part in the making of the ooze which is him creating his own defeat in a way. Karma in the shape of TMNTs. April even faints at the sight of them which is also accurate (should've been Splinter but it's a pretty legit reaction to any of the characters really). Once I push all the childish and whiny nitpicks aside, my only complaint is Megan Fox as April O'Neil. Her lack of skill as an actress aside, she simply doesn't look the part in any way shape or form beyond being a woman.

text: I saw this movie yesterday, and it is truly awful. Like most other superhero movies being churned out by Hollywood nowadays, it is 100% pure commercial product and has no depth at all. I understand that it's a superhero movie and it's really meant for kids, but they could have at least tried to throw in at least a little meaningful character development or thought-provoking action, but they didn't. It's nothing but mindless action scene after mindless action scene with flashy special effects that don't even look that good, and the acting is pretty bad. By far the worst and most annoying thing is the extremely blatant product placement they show at various points in the movie. Movies like this are the reason I never willingly go to see movies based on superheroes.

author: HDTrailers

text: So I saw this movie at least 3 times to get a full & honest opinion about it. Luckily the movie was not directed by Michael Bay. If so, there would've been a lot more action than there already was. Now, as uncanny as it was for all of us to have seen Megan Fox casted as April O'Neil (being a very typical move by Michael Bay), she was actually surprisingly decent playing this character. Because Michael Bay didn't direct it, they didn't overly sexualize her character. About the turtles, I actually thought they did a pretty awesome job at bringing out their personalities a lot more in this movie. I feel like I could really see each character for who they are. Overall Splinter could have had a little more character development but I think he was okay. Shredder on the other hand was completely over done. I think they should have stuck with the idea of him being more of a man than a man in a robotic samurai suit. That was probably the only thing I found extremely bad about the movie was Shredder's character development which I already predicted seeing this trailer. So overall I give this movie a 3 our of 5.

text: I think you should stop complaining about Michael Bay ruining Transformers and Ninja Turtles, I'm not defending his movies, but here it is:  - There are still some recent Transformers and Ninja Turtles cartoons that most people that watched, liked, even the long-time fans, go check Transformers Prime and Nickelodeon's TMNT cartoon.  - Most of these live-action movies based on cartoons, anime, toys and video games suck anyway, and many of these franchises stayed strong after these failures and reverted to their roots.  - As I heard, The Ninja Turtles live-action movies from the 1990s aren't that good either, people love them today because of nostalgia, the first one is mixed, the second one is hated, the third one is considered one of the worst movies ever.  - The Ninja Turtles franchise was really whored in the 90s, go search for all the nonsensical licensed products they had back then, the live-action series, and the rock concert, if it wasn't ruining back then, why it's ruining only now?  - The classic Ninja Turtles and Transformers versions you liked won't stop existing because of the new versions, Michael Bay is not sending people to your homes to destroy all the copies you have of these classic shows.  - Michael Bay is just a producer in this one, not a director  - Your childhood is a lie, I'm not saying these shows were bad, they were cool for their time, but Ninja Turtles started as an indie comic book that was violent, dark, gritty and bloody, and was a parody of comics like these, the original cartoon that everyone loves, was made just to sell the toys, so they needed to make it childish, goofy, hip and full of slang, and tone down the violence, doesn't this sounds like ruining? Also the Transformers cartoon was created to sell the toys, and to this day Transformers is all this, check out the page "To sell toys" in the Transformers Wiki to see how the plot of all Transformers is written to sell as many toys as possible, all of you are overprotecting two long toy commercials.  Now, a counter argument I can agree, is that the main Transformers media became the movies, people know the Transformers more because of the movies than the cartoons, but it's ok, same goes with Marvel and DC superheroes that are more known  by movies and shows than with the comics.

text: As a longtime fan of the original animated series (I vividly remember waking up early nearly every Saturday morning to watch it back in the late 80's and early 90's) and even a bit of the animated '03 update, I actually found this movie to be surprisingly good! Granted, it's still not quite as good as the 1990 live-action movie (which I grew up with), but for what it was, it IS enjoyable! Also, the original nicely carries that 90's vibe, whereas this version nicely carries that 2010's vibe. Both are great in their own ways. The original also follows the dark and gritty atmosphere of the comics more (while still keeping the colored bandanas of the Turtles intact), while this one follows the more lighthearted and campy atmosphere of the 1980's and 2000's cartoon shows. While this film has its faults and will never win any awards, it still succeeds at what it intends to be: a fun, action-packed popcorn flick! Put simply, it is not as bad as some have made it out to be.
